A Jira MCP server is an integration layer that allows AI assistants like Claude, Cursor, or Windsurf to interact with Atlassian Jira using the Model Context Protocol [1][2][3]. These servers expose Jira's functionality as standardized tools, enabling natural language control over issues, projects, sprints, and workflows [2][4][5].

Multiple implementations are available depending on your infrastructure:

Self-hosted servers run locally or in your environment, providing full control and data privacy [1][5]. For example, you can deploy a Node.js or Bun-based server (such as liteart/jira-mcp or zhiyue/jira-mcp) locally using STDIO transport [1][6][3].

Alternatively, some projects offer hosted instances where you point your MCP client to a URL (e.g., `https://mcp-jira-server.onrender.com/mcp`) and provide your own Jira credentials via request headers [2].

For Jira Data Center users, native plugins like mrkhachaturov/jira-mcp-plugin run directly inside the Jira JVM, avoiding external proxies by communicating directly with the local REST API [5].

To integrate with an MCP client, you typically update your configuration file (often `claude_desktop_config.json`):

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "jira": {
      "command": "node",
      "args": ["/path/to/jira-mcp/index.js"],
      "env": {
        "JIRA_URL": "https://your-domain.atlassian.net",
        "JIRA_API_TOKEN": "your-api-token"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Most servers support both Jira Cloud and Data Center by setting environment variables for the instance type and API authentication [6][7][8].
